<ol>
<li><p><strong>Multiplication of two numbers with the same base and different exponents.</strong> Add the exponents together:</p>
<p><math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>a</mi></msup><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>b</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow></msup><mi>.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">x^a x^b=x^{a+b}.</annotation></semantics></math></p></li>

<li><p><strong>Division of two numbers with the same base and different exponents.</strong> Subtract the bottom exponent from the top exponent: <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>a</mi></msup><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>b</mi></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow></msup><mi>.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\frac{x^a}{x^b}=x^{a-b}.</annotation></semantics></math></p></li>

<li><p><strong>Negative exponents.</strong> Take the reciprocal, but change the negative exponent to a positive one:</p>
<p><math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>a</mi></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>a</mi></msup></mfrac><mi>.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">x^{-a}=\frac{1}{x^a}.</annotation></semantics></math></p></li>

<li><p><strong>Exponents of 0.</strong> <math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><msup><mn>0</mn><mn>0</mn></msup><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">0^0</annotation></semantics></math> is undefined, but taking any other number to the zero power produces 1:</p>
<p><math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mrow><mtext mathvariant="normal"> for any </mtext><mspace width="0.333em"></mspace></mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>≠</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">x^0=1 \text{   for any   }x\neq 0.</annotation></semantics></math></p></li>

<li><p><strong>Exponents of 1.</strong> Taking the first power of any number returns the number: <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mrow><mtext mathvariant="normal"> for all </mtext><mspace width="0.333em"></mspace></mrow><mi>x</mi><mi>.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">x^1=x\text{   for all   }x.</annotation></semantics></math></p></li>

<li><p><strong>Multiple layers of exponents.</strong> Multiply the different layers together: <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>a</mi></msup><msup><mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mo><mi>b</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow></msup><mi>.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">(x^a)^b=x^{ab}.</annotation></semantics></math></p></li>

<li><p><strong>Multiplication of numbers with different bases and the same exponent.</strong> The product of the different bases can be set to the common exponent: <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>a</mi></msup><msup><mi>y</mi><mi>a</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><msup><mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mo><mi>a</mi></msup><mi>.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">x^ay^a=(xy)^a.</annotation></semantics></math></p></li>

<li><p><strong>Division of numbers with different bases and the same exponent.</strong> The fraction of the different bases can be set to the common exponent: <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>a</mi></msup><msup><mi>y</mi><mi>a</mi></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo minsize="2.4" maxsize="2.4" stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mo><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi></mfrac><msup><mo minsize="2.4" maxsize="2.4" stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mo><mi>a</mi></msup><mi>.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\frac{x^a}{y^a}=\bigg(\frac{x}{y}\bigg)^a.</annotation></semantics></math></p></li>
</ol>

<ol>
<li><p><math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi></mi><mi>a</mi></msub><msub><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt><mi>b</mi></msub><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac></msup><msup><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>b</mi></mfrac></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>b</mi></mfrac></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfrac></msup><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfrac></msup><msub><mo>=</mo><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow></msub><msqrt><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow></msup></msqrt><mi>.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">_a\sqrt{x}_b\sqrt{x}=x^{\frac{1}{a}}x^{\frac{1}{b}}=x^{\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}}=x^{\frac{a+b}{ab}}=({x^{a+b}})^{\frac{1}{ab}}=_{ab}\sqrt{x^{a+b}}.</annotation></semantics></math><br />
</p></li>
<li><p><math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi></mi><mi>a</mi></msub><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt></mrow><mrow><msub><mi></mi><mi>b</mi></msub><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac></msup><msup><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>b</mi></mfrac></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>b</mi></mfrac></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfrac></msup><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>a</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfrac></msup><msub><mo>=</mo><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow></msub><msqrt><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>a</mi></mrow></msup></msqrt><mi>.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\frac{_a\sqrt{x}}{_b\sqrt{x}}=\frac{x^{\frac{1}{a}}}{x^{\frac{1}{b}}}=x^{\frac{1}{a}-\frac{1}{b}}=x^{\frac{b-a}{ab}}=({x^{b-a}})^{\frac{1}{ab}}=_{ab}\sqrt{x^{b-a}}.</annotation></semantics></math><br />
</p></li>
<li><p><math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi></mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>a</mi></mrow></msub><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><msub><mi></mi><mi>a</mi></msub><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt></mrow></mfrac><mi>.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">_{-a}\sqrt{x}=x^{-\frac{1}{a}}=\frac{1}{x^{\frac{1}{a}}}=\frac{1}{_a\sqrt{x}}.</annotation></semantics></math><br />
</p></li>
<li><p><math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi></mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">_1\sqrt{x}=x</annotation></semantics></math> for all <math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mi>x</mi><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">x</annotation></semantics></math>, so we never consider these <em>first</em> roots.<br />
</p></li>
<li><p><math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi></mi><mi>b</mi></msub><msqrt><mrow><msub><mi></mi><mi>a</mi></msub><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt></mrow></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac></msup><msup><mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>b</mi></mfrac></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfrac></msup><msub><mo>=</mo><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow></msub><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">_b\sqrt{_a\sqrt{x}}=(x^\frac{1}{a})^\frac{1}{b}=x^{\frac{1}{ab}}=_{ab}\sqrt{x}</annotation></semantics></math>.<br />
</p></li>
<li><p><math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi></mi><mi>a</mi></msub><msub><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt><mi>a</mi></msub><msqrt><mi>y</mi></msqrt><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac></msup><msup><mi>y</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac></msup><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><msup><mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac></msup><msub><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi></msub><msqrt><mrow><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi></mrow></msqrt></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">_a\sqrt{x}_a\sqrt{y}=x^{\frac{1}{a}}y^{\frac{1}{a}}=(xy)^{\frac{1}{a}}=_a\sqrt{xy}</annotation></semantics></math>.</p></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Step 1.</strong> Find the LCD. Here LCD<math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>6</mn><mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">(4,6)=12</annotation></semantics></math>.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Step 2.</strong> For each fraction, multiply the numerator and denominator by the number that makes the denominator equal to the LCD. For the first fraction, that number is 3 since <math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">4\times3=12</annotation></semantics></math>, and for the second fraction that number is 2. So, changing the fractions, we obtain <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>12</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>12</mn></mfrac><mi>.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\frac{3\times3}{4\times3}+\frac{5\times2}{6\times2}=\frac{9}{12}+\frac{10}{12}.</annotation></semantics></math></p></li>
<li><p><strong>Step 3.</strong> Add the numerators, and leave the common denominator alone: <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>12</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>12</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>19</mn><mn>12</mn></mfrac><mi>.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\frac{9}{12}+\frac{10}{12}=\frac{19}{12}.</annotation></semantics></math></p></li>
</ul>
<ol>
<li><p>How many possible AES-128 keys are there? Write your answer with an exponent, but in addition, to have a sense of how large this number is, use Stata, R, or a similar program to write out the number approximately. (<em>Hint</em>: The notation “e+10” means that you should move the decimal point 10 places to the right, so 1.23e+10 is 12,300,000,000.)</p></li>
<li><p>Suppose that a supercomputer can check 1,000,000,000,000,000 (1 quadrillion) possible AES-128 keys every second. Approximately how long (<em>hint</em>: in <em>years</em>) would it take the computer to test every possible AES-128 key?</p></li>
<li><p>In theory, but probably not yet in reality, there can exist something called a quantum computer that uses the laws of quantum physics to perform many computations at once.</p></li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p>Consider a problem that has these four properties:</p>
<ol>
<li><p>The only way to solve it is to guess answers repeatedly and check them,</p></li>
<li><p>the number of possible answers to check is the same as the number of inputs,</p></li>
<li><p>every possible answer takes the same amount of time to check, and</p></li>
<li><p>there are no clues about which answers might be better: generating possibilities randomly is just as good as checking them in some special order.</p></li>
</ol>
<p>For problems with all four properties, the time for a quantum computer to solve this will be proportional to the square root of the number of inputs. (From the Wikipedia page on quantum computers.)<a href="#fn1" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref1"><sup>1</sup></a></p>
</blockquote>
